**:The Derzhprom building is a large rectangular structure that measures approximately 63 meters by 142 meters. It is 12 stories tall and has a total floor area of over 70,000 square meters. The building is constructed from reinforced concrete and is notable for its distinctive, angular shape. The façade of the Derzhprom building is divided into a grid of rectangular panels, which are outlined in dark gray metal. The panels are filled with light gray stucco and are separated by narrow strips of windows. The windows are rectangular and are framed in black metal. The panels and windows are arranged in a regular, symmetrical pattern across the façade. The entrance to the Derzhprom building is located in the center of the façade and is marked by a large, arched doorway. The doorway is flanked by two sets of narrow, rectangular windows and is topped by a circular window. The circular window is surrounded by a geometric pattern of dark gray metal. Above the entrance, the façade of the Derzhprom building is divided into two sections. The lower section is divided into a grid of rectangular panels, while the upper section is divided into a series of triangular panels. The triangular panels are oriented in different directions, giving the building a dynamic, angular appearance. The roof of the Derzhprom building is flat and is surrounded by a low parapet. The parapet is decorated with a series of stylized, geometric shapes that are outlined in dark gray metal. Overall, the Derzhprom building is a striking example of Soviet Constructivist architecture. Its bold, angular shape and innovative use of materials and design elements make it a unique and important landmark in the history of modern architecture.** - <@1077899329685168128> (fast)
